&lt;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/humanities/domains/sociology/domains/work/domains/governance/domains/hohfeldian/terms/hohfeldian-appeal/>
  rdf:type schema:Article ;
  schema:url &lt;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/humanities/domains/sociology/domains/work/domains/governance/domains/hohfeldian/terms/hohfeldian-appeal/> ;
  schema:name "Appeal" ;
  schema:description "An Appeal is a quadruple (J₁, J₂, φ, λ) — a lower jurisdiction J₁, an appellate jurisdiction J₂ at a higher depth level, a judgment φ ∈ H*_{t*}^(n) settled at depth n, and an appeal standing λ held by the appellant. The appeal carries φ from J₁'s fiber at depth n to J₂'s fiber at depth k ≥ n via the depth-filtration fiber level transition map ι_{n,k}(t). The defining structure: the appellate fiber at depth k is richer than J₁'s fiber at depth n — it contains more distinguished propositions, more fine-grained normative distinctions, and higher institutional authority. The transferring nucleus asymmetry (ι_{n,k} preserves σ-fixed points exactly but not Δ-fixed points) means that on appeal, propositions settled at the lower level remain provisionally present but propositions that transferred at the lower level may be re-examined. Formally: the appeal is the composition of ι_{n,k} with the appellate forum's adjudication act." ;
  schema:datePublished "2026-03-20" ;
  schema:dateModified "2026-03-20" ;
  schema:about &lt;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/humanities/domains/sociology/domains/work/domains/governance/domains/hohfeldian/terms/hohfeldian-appeal/> ;
